c and splenic arteries","Left gastric, splenic and common hepatic arteries","Splenic, short gastric and left gastroepiploic arteries"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe coeliac artery divides into three major branches: the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastric artery\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic artery\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon hepatic artery\u003C/strong\u003E. This trifurcation is sometimes called the celiac trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft gastric, right gastric and gastroduodenal arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The right gastric and gastroduodenal arteries are branches of the common hepatic artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommon hepatic, proper hepatic and right gastric arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The proper hepatic and right gastric arteries are branches of the common hepatic artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior mesenteric, inferior mesenteric and splenic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The superior and inferior mesenteric arteries are separate branches from the abdominal aorta\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenic, short gastric and left gastroepiploic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The short gastric and left gastroepiploic arteries are branches of the splenic artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe coeliac artery arises from the abdominal aorta at the level of the T12 vertebra and supplies blood to the foregut derivatives including the stomach, proximal duodenum, liver, gallbladder, pancreas and spleen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The coeliac artery supplies the foregut derivatives including the stomach, proximal duodenum, liver, gallbladder, pancreas and spleen.","The coeliac artery branches into three major vessels: left gastric, common hepatic and splenic arteries.","The coeliac artery arises from the abdominal aorta at the level of the T12 vertebra."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Drake R. Gray\u2019s Atlas of Anatomy. 3rd ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59512"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17350"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59512"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T09:13:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T08:28:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10040"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74036"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https: